When building AI systems, developers often face trade-offs. A trade-off means improving one aspect of the model may reduce another aspect.

This lesson focuses on three major trade-offs:

Interpretability vs Performance
Safety vs Transparency
Model Controllability
1. Interpretability vs Explainability

These two concepts are related but not the same.

Interpretability

Interpretability means humans can directly understand how the model works internally.

It gives access to:

Model structure
Feature weights
Decision rules

This allows humans to see exactly how predictions are generated.

Example:

A linear regression model where you can clearly see how each feature affects the prediction.

Typical interpretability models:

Linear regression
Logistic regression
Decision trees

These models allow developers to inspect internal mechanics.

Explainability

Explainability means describing model behavior in human terms, even if the model is complex.

Explainability methods analyze inputs and outputs instead of internal mechanics.

Examples of explainability techniques:

Partial dependence plots
SHAP values
Surrogate models

These methods help explain why the model made a prediction, even when the model itself is a black box.

Key Difference
Interpretability	Explainability
Understand internal mechanics	Explain model behavior
Direct transparency	Indirect explanation
Works with simpler models	Works with complex models
2. Interpretability vs Performance Trade-Off

There is often a trade-off between model interpretability and model performance.

High Interpretability → Lower Performance

Simple models:

Linear regression
Logistic regression
Decision trees

Advantages:

Easy to understand
Transparent
Easy to debug

Disadvantages:

May not capture complex patterns
Lower predictive accuracy
High Performance → Lower Interpretability

Complex models:

Deep neural networks
Large language models
Ensemble models

Advantages:

Higher accuracy
Better at complex tasks

Disadvantages:

Hard to interpret
Hard to debug

These are often called black box models.

When to Choose Interpretability

High interpretability is required in:

Healthcare
Finance
Legal systems
Government decisions

In these areas, humans must understand decisions.

When Explainability Is Used

If a company wants high performance but still wants some understanding, explainability methods are used.

Example:

Explaining predictions of a neural network using SHAP values.

3. Model Safety

Model safety means ensuring AI systems do not cause harm.

Harm can include:

Bias or discrimination
Privacy violations
Security vulnerabilities
Incorrect high-risk decisions

Responsible AI must ensure that models protect individuals and society.

Safety vs Transparency Trade-Off

There is often a conflict between model safety and model transparency.

Transparency requires revealing information, while safety sometimes requires protecting information.

Important factors to balance:

Accuracy
Privacy
Safety
Security

Example:

If too much model information is exposed, attackers might exploit vulnerabilities.

4. Model Controllability

Model controllability means how much developers can control model behavior.

A controllable model allows developers to:

Adjust training data
Influence predictions
Reduce bias
Improve fairness

Higher controllability helps developers steer models toward desired outcomes.

How Controllability Is Measured

Controllability is measured by how model predictions change when developers modify:

Training data
Input features
Data distribution

If small data changes lead to predictable changes in model behavior, the model is controllable.

Model Architecture and Controllability

Model architecture affects controllability.

High Controllability

Simple models:

Linear models
Decision trees

These are easier to control and debug.

Low Controllability

Complex models:

Deep neural networks
Large generative models

These models are harder to control.

Improving Controllability

Developers can improve controllability using:

Data augmentation

Adding more examples to training data.

Training constraints

Adding rules during training to guide model behavior.

Bias correction techniques

Balancing datasets.

Quick Memory Summary

Remember I.P.S.C

I → Interpretability vs performance trade-off
P → Performance increases with complex models
S → Safety vs transparency balance
C → Controllability helps steer model behavior
